# migrated from tests/cases/abduce.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test abduce]
# gen131 (L16/L19): ABDUCTION — inference to the missing premise, the inverse of
# deduction and the mirror of gen129's subtraction. gen129 removed a belief and
# watched a conclusion fall; abduction starts from a conclusion that does NOT
# hold and runs the rule engine BACKWARDS to name the belief that would entail
# it. Computed from the real rules (kb_rule_body_preds), not guessed.

# No rule concludes "wizard", so there is honestly nothing that would make it so.
> what would make socrates a wizard?
< I have no rule that would make anything a wizard, so I can't say what would.

# Teach the rule but NOT its premise: socrates is not (yet) provably mortal.
> every man is a mortal
< Learned rule: mortal(X) :- man(X).
> is socrates a mortal?
< No.

# Abduction: the goal fails, so name the premise that WOULD entail it.
> what would make socrates a mortal?
< If you told me that socrates is a man, then socrates would be a mortal — that's the rule man -> mortal.

# Supply exactly that premise — and gen103's self-correction volunteers the
# downstream consequence the abduction predicted. Two generations composing.
> socrates is a man
< Learned: man(socrates). Now socrates is a mortal after all.
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.
# gen135: contrastive why-not uses the same missing-premise analysis, but now
# explains a failed conclusion directly instead of requiring "what would make".
> every friendly dog is a goodboy
< Learned rule: goodboy(X) :- friendly(X), dog(X).
> rex is a dog
< Learned: dog(rex).
> why isn't rex a goodboy?
< rex is not a goodboy because I am missing: rex is a friendly. The rule is friendly and dog -> goodboy.


# Now the goal HOLDS, so the same question is deduction, not abduction: it cites
# the real proof instead of an antecedent.
> why might socrates be a mortal?
< I already conclude that: mortal(socrates) because man(socrates).

